  htop	--Interactive and colorful process viewer.
  >> kill is used to terminate (stop) a running process by sending it a signal.
  renuka@Bunny:~$ ps -ef
UID        PID  PPID  C STIME TTY          TIME CMD
root         1     0  0 06:46 ?        00:00:00 /init
root         8     1  0 06:47 tty1     00:00:00 /init
renuka       9     8  0 06:47 tty1     00:00:00 -bash
renuka     850     9  0 12:25 tty1     00:00:00 ps -ef
renuka@Bunny:~$ kill 850
-bash: kill: (850) - No such process
When you run ps -ef, that ps command itself is a process.

It runs for a very short time (just enough to show you the list), then immediately ends.

So by the time you copy its PID (850) and type kill 850, the process is already gone.

Thatâ€™s why the system says:no such preocess 

so we can use sleep command here:
The sleep command in Linux is used to pause or delay execution for a specified amount of time (in seconds, minutes, or hours).
sleep 5>> ðŸ‘‰ Pauses the terminal for 5 seconds before continuing.
O/P: renuka@Bunny:~$ sleep 8000 & >>This runs for 8000 seconds. Youâ€™ll get a PID
[2] 885
renuka@Bunny:~$ ps -ef | grep sleep
renuka     875     9  0 12:37 tty1     00:00:00 sleep 600
renuka     885     9  0 12:38 tty1     00:00:00 sleep 8000
renuka     887     9  0 12:38 tty1     00:00:00 grep --color=auto sleep
renuka@Bunny:~$ kill 875
renuka@Bunny:~$ ps -ef | grep sleep
renuka     885     9  0 12:38 tty1     00:00:00 sleep 8000
renuka     889     9  0 12:38 tty1     00:00:00 grep --color=auto sleep
[1]-  Terminated              sleep 600
 ----------------------------------------
 kill -9 <pid>
 Forcefully terminates a process using signal 9
 kill â†’ sends a polite request to stop (signal 15).
kill -9 â†’ forcefully kills it immediately (signal 9).
example
renuka@Bunny:~$ sleep 9000 &
[4] 893
renuka@Bunny:~$ ps -ef | grep sleep
renuka     885     9  0 12:38 tty1     00:00:00 sleep 8000
renuka     890     9  0 12:41 tty1     00:00:00 sleep 1000
renuka     893     9  0 12:43 tty1     00:00:00 sleep 9000
renuka     895     9  0 12:43 tty1     00:00:00 grep --color=auto sleep
renuka@Bunny:~$ kill -9 885
renuka@Bunny:~$ ps -ef | grep sleep
renuka     890     9  0 12:41 tty1     00:00:00 sleep 1000
renuka     893     9  0 12:43 tty1     00:00:00 sleep 9000
renuka     897     9  0 12:43 tty1     00:00:00 grep --color=auto sleep
[2]   Killed                  sleep 8000
--------------------------------------------------
pkill >> process kill (It kills a process by name, not by PID.)
renuka@Bunny:~$ sleep 1000 &
[1] 904
renuka@Bunny:~$ sleep 4000 &
[2] 905
renuka@Bunny:~$ ps -ef | grep sleep
renuka     904     9  0 12:52 tty1     00:00:00 sleep 1000
renuka     905     9  0 12:52 tty1     00:00:00 sleep 4000
renuka     907     9  0 12:52 tty1     00:00:00 grep --color=auto sleep
renuka@Bunny:~$ pkill sleep
[1]-  Terminated              sleep 1000
[2]+  Terminated              sleep 4000
renuka@Bunny:~$ ps -ef | grep sleep
renuka     910     9  9 12:53 tty1     00:00:00 grep --color=auto sleep
------------------------------------------------
Suppose you have these processes:

sleep 300
sleeper.sh
sleepy_cat

pkill sleep â†’ kills all three, because it matches â€œsleepâ€ anywhere in the name.

killall sleep â†’ kills only the one exactly named sleep.

ðŸ§  Summary:

âœ… pkill â†’ pattern match (flexible, silent)
âœ… killall â†’ exact name match (prints output)
